[start section id="20112"]

Reviewed colonoscopy, pathology, and doctor's notes.
#1 Descending colon mass suspicious for carcinoma
Mrs. Redman is referred for treatment of a colon mass that is suspicious for carcinoma.  We will repeat colonoscopy on the complex list with anesthesia, given her comorbidities.  Certainly, if this does not appear malignant, perhaps endoscopic treatment could be considered.  However, I am not optimistic this will be possible.  Biopsies will be obtained for immunohistochemistry staining, given her multiplicity of colon cancers and a family history of uterine cancer.  Given her renal insufficiency, we will not obtain CT or MRI but will stage her with a liver ultrasound and a PET scan.  Lab studies are pending including CBC, chemistry panel, and CEA.  Once these are obtained, the patient will meet with a colorectal surgeon.  I have informed the patient that annual flexible sigmoidoscopy will be necessary for any remaining bowel after resection.
#2 Preoperative medical evaluation
Will request cardiology evaluation prior to surgery.  She is satisfactory for purposes of colonoscopy.  Her laboratory studies, chest x-ray, and ECG will be obtained today.
Discussed with Dr. Jean Gonzalez, note to follow.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

